# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1905-new-york-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1905-new-york-giants-season] The **1905 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 23rd season, and the team won their second consecutive National League pennant.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1905-new-york-giants-season] They beat the Philadelphia Athletics in the World Series.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1905-new-york-giants-season] This team featured three Hall of Fame players – catcher Roger Bresnahan, and pitchers Christy Mathewson and Joe McGinnity – along with Hall of Fame manager John McGraw.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1905-new-york-giants-season] Mathewson won the pitching triple crown and then had one of the greatest World Series performances of all-time, with three shutouts in six days.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1905-new-york-giants-season] Only six men pitched for the Giants in 1905.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1905-new-york-giants-season] The offense, led by "Turkey" Mike Donlin, scored the most runs in the majors.
[src:1905-new-york-giants-season/1905-new-york-giants-season] On June 29, Archie "Moonlight" Graham, made famous through the novel *Shoeless Joe* and subsequent movie *Field of Dreams*, made his lone major league appearance.
